{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chart-page-js","path":"/area-chart","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>displays data as the area between the data curve and the horizontal axis. Area charts emphasize the change of a single variable by connecting individual data points. </p>\n<!--more-->\n<p>The <strong><em>X-axis</em></strong> has a numeric or a categorical scale. The <strong><em>Y-axis</em></strong> is usually categorical. <strong><em>Value markers</em></strong> typically indicate individual data points when few of them appear in the chart.</p>\n<p>The purpose of an area chart is visualizing the change of a single variable. Functionally, area charts are the same as <a href=\"/line-chart\">line charts</a>. Visually, using the area instead of a line makes the shape of the data more noticeable. Especially for multi-line charts and stacked or grouped area charts the filled area below the data curve improves the chart's readability. </p>\n<p>Even though an area chart consists of individual data points, its purpose is not in communicating a set of specific values but in showing their relationships. For this reason, the data points typically do not have labels.</p>\n<p>Area charts are used forindicating trends, comparing trends, their changes, and relationships between values. Color and texture can emphasize these relationships. <sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup></p>\n<p>Like <a href=\"/bar-chart\">bar charts</a>, area charts emphasize change and trends. But an area chart can display more data points in the same space. </p>\n<p>Area charts can have three types of data curves depending on their data aggregation method: segmented, stepped, and smoothed.</p>\n<p>William Playfair introduced area charts in 1786 in his book <em>The Commercial and Political Atlas</em>.</p>\n<h2 id=\"alternatives\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#alternatives\" aria-label=\"alternatives permalink\" class=\"anchorLink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Alternatives</h2>\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"/line-chart\"><em>Bar chart</em></a> displays the relationship of a category to a numeric variable as the height a rectangle bar.</li>\n<li><a href=\"/line-chart\"><em>Line chart</em></a>, functionally the same as an area chart, a line chart is more suitable for cases where multiple line charts are displayed in the same graph space.</li>\n<li><a href=\"/stream-graph\"><em>Streamgraph</em></a> is a type of stacked area chart aligned relative to central axis. Streamgraphs have a smoothed curve. They are normally oriented horizontally.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2 id=\"further-reading\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#further-reading\" aria-label=\"further reading permalink\" class=\"anchorLink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Further reading</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area_chart\">Area chart</a> article on Wikipedia.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"references\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#references\" aria-label=\"references permalink\" class=\"anchorLink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>References</h2>\n<div class=\"footnotes\">\n<hr>\n<ol>\n<li id=\"fn-1\">\n<p>Harris, Robert L. <a href=\"https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&#x26;lr=&#x26;id=qusmDAAAQBAJ\"><em>Information graphics: A comprehensive illustrated reference.</em></a> Oxford University Press, 2000. p. 10</p>\n<a href=\"#fnref-1\" class=\"footnote-backref\">↩</a>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</div>","excerpt":"displays data as the area between the data curve and the horizontal axis. Area charts emphasize the change of a single variable by…","overview":"<p>displays data as the area between the data curve and the horizontal axis. Area charts emphasize the change of a single variable by…</p>","fields":{"variationOf":null},"frontmatter":{"title":"area chart","synonyms":null,"functions":["change over time"],"visualizationTechniques":null,"informationTypes":null,"axisDirections":null,"examples":[{"title":"Interest of the National Debt from the Revolution, 1786","link":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area_chart#/media/File:1786_Playfair_-_25_Interest_of_the_national_Debt_from_the_Revolution.jpg","note":null,"image":"playfair-national-debt.jpg"},{"title":"Breakdown of China's Population By Age Group","link":"https://ourworldindata.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/Internet-users-by-world-region.png","note":null,"image":"china-population.png"},{"title":"Thirty Years of Atlantic Hurricanes","link":"https://www.axios.com/thirty-years-of-atlantic-hurricanes-1513305322-8b3c056a-ff13-49dc-a95d-961481119907.html","note"